<ComingSoonRoomLayout
  room="records"
  title="Records Room"
  subtitle="Primary sources, originals and copies."
  sourceId="coming-soon-records"
>
  <p>
    The Records Room will hold the original documents that made the school
    trust possible — the Land Ordinance of 1785, the Northwest Ordinance of
    1787, the Enabling Act of every federal-grant state, the surveyors' notes
    that drew the section lines, the court opinions that built the fiduciary
    doctrine, and the trust-fund statutes that turned land into capital.
    Where a record is in the public domain, we hold the scan; where it
    isn't, we hold a careful citation so a reader can find it.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why this room matters.</strong> Most of what's known about
    America's school trust has lived in scattered archives — federal land
    offices, state historical societies, university special collections,
    county courthouse basements. The Records Room gathers it into one place
    for the first time, and gives every claim made elsewhere in the Library
    a paper it can be cited to.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>What you won't find here.</strong> Records lost to the 1906 San
    Francisco earthquake fire, the 1881 Albany capitol fire, and a dozen
    smaller courthouse losses. The Library can hold what survives. It can't
    recover what burned. Where a gap is structural, we say so.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Being planned.</strong> Drafting the federal Enabling Acts
    first — twenty-eight of them — in the order Library readers ask for
    them.
  </p>
</ComingSoonRoomLayout>
